obert\n  |url        = http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/tnoslist.html\n  |accessdate = 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-CEN-SDO-list\">{{cite web\n  |title      = List Of Centaurs and Scattered-Disk Objects\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/t_centaurs.html\n  |accessdate = 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\">{{cite web\n  |title      = ''MPC'' 112429-112436\n  |work       = MPC/MPO/MPS Archive\n  |author     = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/2019/MPC_20190406.pdf\n  |date       = 6 April 2019\n  |accessdate = 9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Schindler-2017\">{{Cite journal\n  |display-authors = 6\n  |first1     = K. |last1 = Schindler\n  |first2     = J. |last2 = Wolf\n  |first3     = J. |last3 = Bardecker\n  |first4     = A. |last4 = Olsen\n  |first5     = T. |last5 = M\u00fcller\n  |first6     = C. |last6 = Kiss\n  |first7     = J. L. |last7 = Ortiz\n  |first8     = F. |last8 = Braga-Ribas\n  |first9     = J. I. B. |last9 = Camargo\n  |first10    = D. |last10 = Herald\n  |first11    = A. |last11 = Krabbe\n  |date       = April 2017\n  |title      = Results from a triple chord stellar occultation and far-infrared photometry of the trans-Neptunian object (229762) 2007 UK126\n  |url        = https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2017/04/aa28620-16.pdf\n  |journal    = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n  |volume     = 600\n  |page       = 16\n  |bibcode    = 2017A&A...600A..12S\n  |doi        = 10.1051/0004-6361/201628620\n  |arxiv      = 1611.02798\n  |access-date= 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Benedetti-Rossi-2016\">{{Cite journal\n  |display-authors = 6\n  |first1     = G. |last1 = Benedetti-Rossi\n  |first2     = B. |last2 = Sicardy\n  |first3     = M. W. |last3 = Buie\n  |first4     = J. L. |last4 = Ortiz\n  |first5     = R. |last5 = Vieira-Martins\n  |first6     = J. M. |last6 = Keller\n  |first7     = F. |last7 = Braga-Ribas\n  |first8     = J. I. B. |last8 = Camargo\n  |first9     = M. |last9 = Assafin\n  |first10    = N. |last10 = Morales\n  |first11    = R. |last11 = Duffard\n  |first12    = A. |last12 = Dias-Oliveira\n  |first13    = P. |last13 = Santos-Sanz\n  |first14    = J. |last14 = Desmars\n  |last15 = Gomes-J\u00fa\n  |first16    = A. R. |last16 = nior\n  |first17    = R. |last17 = Leiva\n  |first18    = J. |last18 = Bardecker\n  |first19    = J. K., Jr. |last19 = Bean\n  |first20    = A. M. |last20 = Olsen\n  |first21    = D. W. |last21 = Ruby\n  |first22    = R. |last22 = Sumner\n  |first23    = A. |last23 = Thirouin\n  |last24 = G\u00f3mez-Mu\u00f1\n  |first25    = M. A. |last25 = oz\n  |first26    = L. |last26 = Gutierrez\n  |first27    = L. |last27 = Wasserman\n  |first28    = D. |last28 = Charbonneau\n  |first29    = J. |last29 = Irwin\n  |first30    = S. |last30 = Levine\n  |first31    = B. |last31 = Skiff\n  |date       = December 2016\n  |title      = Results from the 2014 November 15th Multi-chord Stellar Occultation by the TNO (229762) 2007 UK126\n  |journal    = The Astronomical Journal\n  |volume     = 152\n  |issue      = 6\n  |page       = 11\n  |bibcode    = 2016AJ....152..156B\n  |doi        = 10.3847/0004-6256/152/6/156\n  |arxiv      = 1608.01030\n  }}</ref>\n\n}} \n\n<!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www2.lowell.edu/users/grundy/tnbs/229762_2007_UK126.html G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 and G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3h\u00fa], Will Grundy, Lowell Observatory (Last updated: 24 Dec 2018)\n* [http://andrew-lowe.ca/2007uk126.htm 2007 UK126 Precovery Images]\n* [http://tech.groups.yahoo.com/group/mpml/message/20524 3rd largest scattered disk object discovered] (Yahoo Groups)\n* [http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/mpec/K10/K10A05.html 2007 UK126 Minor planet designation number]\n* {{AstDys|229762}}\n* {{JPL small body}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Small Solar System bodies}}\n{{Minor planets navigator| |number=229762 | }}\n{{Solar System moons (compact)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0}}\n[[Category:Scattered disc and detached objects|229762]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by the Palomar Observatory]]\n[[Category:Named minor planets]]\n[[Category:Minor planets named from San mythology]]\n[[Category:Binary trans-Neptunian objects]]\n[[Category:Possible dwarf planets]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 2007|20071019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox planet\n | minorplanet     = yes\n | name            = G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0\n | background      = #C2E0FF\n | image           = 2007 UK126 Hubble.png\n | image_size      = 250\n | caption         = G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 and its satellite G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa, imaged by the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] on 2 January 2018\n | discovery_ref   = &thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /><ref name=\"MPC-CEN-SDO-list\" /><ref name=\"MPEC\" />\n | discoverer      = [[Megan Schwamb|M. E. Schwamb]]<br />[[Michael E. Brown|M. E. Brown]]<br />[[David L. Rabinowitz|D. L. Rabinowitz]]\n | discovery_site  = [[Palomar Observatory|Palomar Obs.]]\n | discovered      = 19 October 2007\n | earliest_precovery_date = 1982\n | mpc_name        = (229762) G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0\n | alt_names       = {{mp|2007 UK|126}}\n | pronounced      = <small>English:</small> {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0261|u\u02d0|n|h|o\u028a|m|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|m|\u0259}}<br /><small>[[Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan language|Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan]]:</small> {{IPA-all|\u1da2\u1d4f\u01c3\u0361\u03c7\u02bc\u1e79\u1d51\u030a\u01c1\u02b0\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0||G\u01c3kun\u01c1'homdima.ogg}}\n | named_after     = G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0&thinsp;<ref name=Grundy2019 /><br />{{small|([[San mythology]])}}\n | mp_category     = {{nowrap|[[Trans-Neptunian object|TNO]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"jpldata\" />{{\u00b7}}[[Scattered disc|Scat-ext]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"Buie\" />}}<br />[[Scattered disc object|SDO]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-CEN-SDO-list\" /><ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" />{{\u00b7}}[[Distant minor planet|distant]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-object\" />\n | orbit_ref       = &thinsp;<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n | epoch           = 27 April 2019 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2458600.5)\n | uncertainty     = 2\n | observation_arc = 36.16 [[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (13,209 d)\n | aphelion        = 107.94 [[Astronomical unit|AU]]\n | perihelion      = 37.502 AU\n | semimajor       = 72.722 AU\n | eccentricity    = 0.4843\n | period          = 620.17 yr (226,517 d)\n | mean_anomaly    = 344.21[[Degree (angle)|\u00b0]]\n | mean_motion     = {{Deg2DMS|0.0016|sup=ms}} / day\n | inclination     = 23.378\u00b0\n | asc_node        = 131.09\u00b0\n | arg_peri        = 346.88\u00b0\n | satellites      = 1<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-BIN\" />\n | dimensions      = {{val|678.0|11}} \u00d7 {{val|611.4|18|u=km}} occultation<ref name=Ortiz2019>{{cite chapter |author= Ortiz, Sicardy, Camargo & Braga-Ribas |chapter= Stellar Occultations by Transneptunian Objects: From Predictions to Observations and Prospects for the Future |title= The Transneptunian Solar System |editor= Prialnik, Barucci & Young |publisher= Elsevier |date= 2019 |url=  https://arxiv.org/ftp/arxiv/papers/1905/1905.04335.pdf }}</ref>\n | mean_diameter   = {{val|642|28}}<ref name=Ortiz2019/><br>{{val|599|-|629|ul=km}}<ref name=\"Schindler-2017\" /><br />{{val|638|+24|-12|u=km}} {{small|sphere-equivalent (elliptical fit)}}<ref name=\"Benedetti-Rossi-2016\" />\n | flattening      = {{val|0.105|0.05|0.04}}<ref name=\"Benedetti-Rossi-2016\" /><br />{{val|0.118|0.055|0.048}}<ref name=\"Benedetti-Rossi-2016\" />\n | mass            = {{val|1.361|0.033|e=20|u=kg}}<ref name=Grundy2019/>{{small|(total system mass)}}\n | density         = {{val|1.04|0.17|u=g/cm3}}, based on an effective diameter of {{val|632|34|u=km}}<ref name=Grundy2019/>\n | rotation        = possibly {{val|11.05|u=h|}},<ref name=Thirouin2014/> within 11 to 41 hours<ref name=Grundy2019/>\n | albedo          = {{val|0.142|0.015}}<ref name=Ortiz2019/><br>{{val|0.150|0.016}}<ref name=\"Schindler-2017\" /><br />{{val|0.159|+0.007|-0.013}}<ref name=\"Benedetti-Rossi-2016\" />\n | spectral_type   = \n | single_temperature=50\u201355 K max.<ref name=\"Schindler-2017\" />\n | magnitude       = 20.8<ref name=\"MPEC\" />\n | abs_magnitude   = 3.3<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /><ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n}}\n\n'''229762 G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0''', provisional designation '''{{mp|2007 UK|126}}''', is a [[trans-Neptunian object]] and [[Binary minor planet|binary system]] from the extended [[scattered disc]], located in the outermost region of the [[Solar System]].<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\" /> It was discovered on 19 October 2007 by American astronomers [[Megan Schwamb]], [[Michael E. Brown|Michael Brown]], and [[David L. Rabinowitz|David Rabinowitz]] at the [[Palomar Observatory]] in California<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /> and measures approximately {{convert|600|km|mi|abbr=off|sigfig=1|sp=us}} in diameter. This medium sized TNO appears to be representative of a class of mid-sized objects under approximately 1000&nbsp;km that have not collapsed into fully solid bodies. Its 100-kilometer [[Minor-planet moon|moon]] was discovered by Keith Noll, Will Grundy, and colleagues with the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] in 2008,<ref>K.S. Noll, W.M. Grundy, S.D. Benecchi, H.F. Levison & E.A. Barker (2009) 'Discovery of eighteen transneptunian binaries', ''Bull. Amer. Astron. Soc.'' 41, 1092 (abstract)</ref><ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" /><ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-BIN\" /><ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" /> and named G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa.\n\n==Names==\n\nThe name ''G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0'' is from the [[Ju\u01c0\u02bchoansi]] ([[\u01c3Kung people|\u01c3Kung]]) people of Namibia. G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 is the Beautiful [[Aardvark]] Girl of Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan mythology, who sometimes appears in the stories of other [[San people]]s as a python girl or elephant girl; she defends her people and punishes wrongdoers using ''g\u01c1\u00e1m\u00edg\u01c1\u00e0m\u00ec'' spines,<ref>''G\u01c1\u00e1m\u00edg\u01c1\u00e0m\u00ec'' is a spiny plant, variously identified, including as ''[[Tribulus terrestris]]'' 'Devil's-thorn'.</ref> a rain-cloud full of hail, and her magical [[Gemsbok|oryx]] horn.<ref name=Grundy2019>{{cite journal |author1=W.M. Grundy |author2=K.S. Noll |author3=M.W. Buie |author4=S.D. Benecchi |author5=D. Ragozzine |author6=H.G. Roe |title=The Mutual Orbit, Mass, and Density of Transneptunian Binary G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 ({{mp|(229762) 2007 UK|126}}) |url=http://www2.lowell.edu/~grundy/abstracts/2019.G-G.html |website=Icarus |accessdate=12 August 2019 |language=English |doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2018.12.037 |date=December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407045339/http://www2.lowell.edu/~grundy/abstracts/preprints/2019.G-G.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2019}}</ref> The name \"G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0\" derives from ''g\u01c3k\u00fan'' 'aardvark', ''\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2m m\u00e0'' 'young woman' and the feminine suffix ''d\u00ed''. The moon G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa is named after her horn: it means simply 'oryx' (''g\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9'') 'horn' (''\u01c3h\u00fa'').<ref>Patrick Dickens (1994) ''English\u2013Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan\u2013English dictionary'', K\u00f6ppe Verlag.</ref> \n\nIn the [[Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan language]], the planet and moon names are pronounced {{IPA-all|\u1da2\u1d4f\u01c3\u0361\u03c7\u02bc\u1e79 \u1d51\u030a\u01c1\u02b0\u00f2md\u00ed m\u00e0||G\u01c3kun\u01c1'homdima.ogg}} and {{IPA-all|\u1da2\u01c3\u00f2\u02c0\u00e9 \u01c3\u02b0\u00fa||G\u01c3o'e \u01c3Hu.ogg}}, respectively. Usually, when speaking English, the [[click consonant]]s in words from Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan and other San languages are simply ignored (much as ''[[wikt:Xhosa|Xhosa]]'' is pronounced {{IPAc-en|'|k|o\u028a|z|\u0259}} ({{respell|KOH|z\u0259|}}) rather than {{IPA-all|\u01c1\u02b0osa|}}), resulting in {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0261|u\u02d0|n|h|o\u028a|m|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|m|\u0259}} ({{respell|GOON|hohm|DEE|m\u0259}}) and {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0261|o\u028a|.|e\u026a|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0}} ({{respell|GOH|ay|HOO|}}) or {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0261|o\u028a|.|e\u026a|\u02c8|k|u\u02d0}} ({{respell|GOH|ay|KOO|}}).\n\n[[ASCII]] renderings of the names would be {{angle bracket|G!kun&#x7C;&#x7C;'homdima}} (or {{angle bracket|G!kun//'homdima}}) for the primary and {{angle bracket|G!o'e !Hu}} or {{angle bracket|G!o'e!hu}} for the secondary.<ref>[https://minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/MPNames.html#G Minor Planet Names: Alphabetical List]</ref>\n\n==Orbit==\n\nG\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 orbits the Sun at a distance of 37.5\u2013107.9&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]] once every 620 years and 2 months (226,517 days; [[semi-major axis]] of 72.72&nbsp;AU). Its orbit has an [[orbital eccentricity|eccentricity]] of 0.48 and an [[orbital inclination|inclination]] of 23[[Degree (angle)|\u00b0]] with respect to the [[ecliptic]].<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n\nAn eccentricity of 0.48 suggests that it was gravitationally [[Perturbation (astronomy)|scattered]] into its current eccentric orbit. It will come to [[apsis|perihelion]] in July 2046, and [[Asteroid occultation|mutual occultation]] events with its satellite will begin in late 2050 and last most of that decade.<ref name=Grundy2019/> It has a bright [[Absolute magnitude#Solar System bodies (H)|absolute magnitude]] of 3.7,<ref name=\"MPC-CEN-SDO-list\" /> and has been observed 178 times over 16 [[Opposition (planets)|oppositions]] with [[precovery]] images back to 1982.<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n\n==Physical characteristics==\nStellar occultation events indicate that G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 has an effective (equivalent-sphere) diameter of 600\u2013670 km, but is not spherical. Due to complications from its non-spherical shape, the rotational period cannot be definitely determined from current [[light curve|light-curve]] data, which has an amplitude of \u0394m = 0.03 \u00b1 0.01 mag,<ref name=Thirouin2014>{{Cite journal|last=Thirouin|first=A.|last2=Noll|first2=K. S.|last3=Ortiz|first3=J. L.|last4=Morales|first4=N.|date=1 September 2014|title=Rotational properties of the binary and non-binary populations in the trans-Neptunian belt|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|language=en|volume=569|page=A3|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201423567|arxiv=1407.1214|bibcode=2014A&A...569A...3T}}</ref> but the simplest solution is 11.05 hours. It is almost certainly between that and 41 hours. The system mass is {{val|1.36|0.03|e=20|u=kg}}, about 2% that of Earth's moon and a bit more than Saturn's moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]]. The moon is unlikely to comprise more than 1% or so of the total. Its geometric albedo is approximately 0.15, and its density approximately 1.<ref name=Grundy2019/> \n\n{{As of|June 2018}}, [[Michael E. Brown|Mike Brown]] lists it as [[List of possible dwarf planets|highly likely to be a dwarf planet]], due to its size.<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" /> However, Grundy et al. propose that the low density and albedo, combined with the fact that TNOs both larger and smaller \u2013 including comets \u2013 have a substantial fraction of rock in their composition, indicate that it and similar objects such as [[174567 Varda]] and [[120347 Salacia]] (in the size range of 400\u20131000 km, with albedos less than \u22480.2 and densities of \u22481.2 g/cm<sup>3</sup> or less) may retain a degree of porosity in their physical structure, having never collapsed and possibly differentiated into planetary bodies like higher density or higher albedo (and presumably resurfaced) [[90482 Orcus]] and [[50000 Quaoar]], or at best are only partially differentiated; such objects would never have been in hydrostatic equilibrium and would not be dwarf planets at present.<ref name=Grundy2019/>\n\n== Satellite ==\n{| class=\"floatleft\"\n|\n{{Infobox planet\n| background = #E6D6C6\n| image = \n| caption = \n| name = G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa\n| discoverer = Noll et al.<ref>K.S. Noll, W.M. Grundy, S.D. Benecchi, H.F. Levison & E.A. Barker (2009) 'Discovery of eighteen transneptunian binaries', ''Bull. Amer. Astron. Soc.'' 41, 1092 (abstract)</ref>\n| discovered = 2008\n| mpc_name = (229762) G\u01c3k\u00fan\u01c1\u02bch\u00f2md\u00edm\u00e0 I G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa\n| pronounced = <small>English:</small>{{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0261|o\u028a|.|e\u026a|\u02c8|k|u\u02d0}} <br><small>[[Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan language|Ju\u01c0\u02bchoan]]:</small> {{IPA-all|\u1da2\u01c3\u00f2\u02c0\u00e9\u01c3\u02b0\u00fa||G\u01c3o'e \u01c3Hu.ogg}}\n| note = yes\n| orbit_ref = <ref name=Grundy2019/>\n| periapsis = \n| apoapsis = \n| semimajor = {{val|6035|48|u=km}}\n| eccentricity = {{val|0.0236|0.0066}}\n| period = {{val|11.31473|0.00016|u=d}} (prograde)\n| inclination = {{val|43.75|0.38|u=\u00b0}} (to J2000 equatorial frame)\n| satellite_of = \n| equatorial_radius = {{val|71|4|u=km}}<ref name=Grundy2019 />\n| magnitude = \n| abs_magnitude = \n}}\n|}\nIt has one known satellite, '''G\u01c3\u00f2\u02bc\u00e9 \u01c3H\u00fa'''. It is one of the reddest known TNOs. Size and mass can only be inferred. The magnitude difference between the two is {{val|3.242|0.039}} mag. This would correspond to a difference in diameter of a factor of {{val|4.45|0.08}}, assuming the same albedo. Red satellites often have lower albedos than their primaries, but that may not be the case with this moon. Such uncertainties do not affect density calculations as the moon has only about 1% the volume, and so is less important than the uncertainties in the primary's diameter.<ref name=Grundy2019/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Palomar Distant Solar System Survey]] (PDSSS)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"jpldata\">{{cite web\n  |type       = 2018-10-15 last obs.\n  |title      = JPL Small-Body Database Browser: 229762 G!kunll'homdima (2007 UK126)\n  |url        = https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2229762\n  |publisher  = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate = 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-object\">{{cite web\n  |title      = 229762 (2007 UK126)\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=229762\n  |accessdate = 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPEC\">{{Cite journal\n  |first1     = M. E. |last1 = Schwamb\n  |first2     = M. E. |last2 = Brown\n  |first3     = D. |last3 = Rabinowitz\n  |first4     = B. G. |last4 = Marsden\n  |date       = February 2008\n  |title      = 2007 UK126\n  |url        = https://minorplanetcenter.net//mpec/K08/K08D38.html\n  |journal    = [[Minor Planet Electronic Circular]]\n  |volume = 2008-D38\n |issue      = 2008-D38 (2008)\n  |bibcode    = 2008MPEC....D...38S\n  |access-date= 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buie\">{{cite web\n  |author=Marc W. Buie\n  |author-link=Marc W. Buie\n  |date=8 May 2012\n  |title=Orbit Fit and Astrometric record for 229762\n  |publisher=SwRI (Space Science Department)\n  |url=http://www.boulder.swri.edu/~buie/kbo/astrom/229762.html\n  |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\">{{cite web\n  |title      = How many dwarf planets are there in the outer solar system?\n  |publisher  = [[California Institute of Technology]]\n  |last       = Brown |first= Michael E.\n  |url        = http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n  |accessdate = 25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-BIN\">{{cite web\n  |title      = Asteroids with Satellites Database \u2013 (229762) G!kunll'homdima and G!o'e!Hu\n  |work       = Johnston's Archive\n  |date       =  20 September 2014\n  |last      