enHart/nov9_hart-ap.html |archivedate=2009-05-31}}\n* {{cite web | url = http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingHarts/nov20_lawsuit-can.html | title = Martha Hart sues Diana over book | author = Greg Oliver | publisher = SLAM! Wrestling | accessdate=2007-06-18 |date=November 20, 2001}}\n\n; Radio\n* {{cite web | url = http://archives.cbc.ca/sports/wrestling/topics/1237-6904/ | title = WEST - Martha Hart's 'day of reckoning (Archived radio Broadcast)|author=This Morning | publisher = CBC |accessdate=2007-06-18 |date=November 20, 2000}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.owenhartfoundation.org/assets/drmarthahartbiography.pdf Martha Hart Biography]\n* {{IMDb name|id=1071646|name=Martha Hart}}\n* [http://www.owenhartfoundation.org/index.html Owen Hart Foundation official website]\n* [http://wrestlingnewscenter.blogspot.com/2009/02/owen-harts-widow-chooses-positive-path.html Martha Hart Interview]\n* [http://conted.ucalgary.ca/championsoflearning/ Champions Of Learning]\n\n{{Hart family}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hart, Martha}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Hart family members]]\n[[Category:Writers from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian sociologists]]\n", "name_user": "Kgywu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added in that Martha Hart is VP of the Angel Film Awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_Hart"}
{"title_page": "History of the Jews in the Dominican Republic", "text_new": "[[File:Centro Israelita de Republica Dominicana.JPG|thumb|right|Inside a [[Centro Israelita de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana|Santo Domingo synagogue]]]]\nThe first [[Jews]] known to have reached the island of [[Hispaniola]] were [[Spanish Jews|Spanish]].\n\nWhen the island was divided by the French and the Spanish, most Jews settled on the Spanish side which would later become the [[Dominican Republic]]. Eventually, [[Sephardim]] from other countries also arrived. In the 19th century Jews from [[Cura\u00e7ao]] settled in Hispaniola, although they did not form a strong community. Most of them hid their Jewish identities or were unaffiliated with Jewish tradition by that time. Among their descendants were Dominican President [[Francisco Henr\u00edquez y Carvajal]]<ref>[http://www.27febrero.com/biografias.htm#FRANCISCO%20HENRIQUEZ%20Y%20CARVAJAL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113182604/http://www.27febrero.com/biografias.htm#ULISES%20FRANCISCO%20ESPAILLAT |date=2008-01-13 }} Biography of Francisco Henr\u00edquez y Carvajal (in Spanish)</ref><ref name=Genealog>{{cite journal |title=Familias capitale\u00f1as: Los Henr\u00edquez |journal=C\u00e1psulas Geneal\u00f3gicas |date=23 August 2010 |issue=1/3 |url=http://hoy.com.do/capsulas-genealogicasfamilias-capitalenas-los-henriquez/ |access-date=3 February 2014 |last=Read|first=Jaime |publisher=Hoy |location=Santo Domingo |language=Spanish |quote=Este apellido se origina en la pen\u00ednsula Ib\u00e9rica, tanto en Portugal como en Espa\u00f1a, de familias jud\u00edas sefard\u00edes que marcharon posteriormente hacia el norte, llegando a Holanda, a ra\u00edz de la expulsi\u00f3n de jud\u00edos luego de la Reconquista. De all\u00ed parten hacia las colonias neerlandesas del Caribe, llegando a Curazao. En la Rep\u00fablica Dominicana, el tronco de esta familia fue Noel Henr\u00edquez Alt\u00edas (n. 25 diciembre de 1813), natural de Curazao}}</ref> and his issue [[Pedro Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]], [[Max Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]], and [[Camila Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]].\n\nThe Dominican Republic was one of the very few countries willing to accept mass Jewish immigration during [[World War II]]. At the [[\u00c9vian Conference]], it offered to accept up to 100,000 Jewish refugees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/article.php?lang=en&ModuleId=10005468|title=German Jewish Refugees, 1933\u20131939|website=www.ushmm.org|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> It is estimated that 5,000 visas were actually issued, and the vast majority of the recipients did not reach the country because of how hard it was to get out of occupied Europe.<ref name=\"bh.org.il\">{{cite web |title=The Jews of the Dominican Republic |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/dominican-republic |publisher=The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot}}</ref> The DORSA (Dominican Republic Settlement Association) was formed with the assistance of the JDC, and helped settle Jews in [[Sos\u00faa]], on the northern coast. About 700 European Jews of [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish descent reached the settlement where each family received {{Convert|33|ha}} of land, 10 cows (plus 2 additional cows per child), a mule and a horse, and a [[US$]]10,000 loan (about {{Inflation|US|10000|1941|r=-3|fmt=c}} dollars at {{currentyear}} prices) at 1% interest.<ref name=MuKienAdrianaSang>{{cite web|last=Sang|first=Mu-Kien Adriana|title=Jud\u00edos en el Caribe. La comunidad jud\u00eda en Sos\u00faa (2)|url=http://www.elcaribe.com.do/2012/11/16/judios-caribe.-comunidad-judia-sosua-2|publisher=El Caribe|access-date=29 May 2014|authorlink=Mu-Kien Adriana Sang|language=Spanish|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529071312/http://www.elcaribe.com.do/2012/11/16/judios-caribe.-comunidad-judia-sosua-2|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html|title=Dominican Republic as Haven for Jewish Refugees|website=www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Other refugees settled in the capital, Santo Domingo. In 1943 the number of known Jews in the Dominican Republic peaked at 1000. Sos\u00faa's Jewish community experienced a deep decline in the 1980s due to emigration during the touristic boom of Sos\u00faa when most Jews sold their land to developers. The oldest Jewish grave is dated to 1826.\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Sephardic Jews]] that were exiled from [[Spain]] and the Mediterranean area in 1492 and 1497,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/History/Inquisition.html |title=The Exile of the Jews due to the Spanish Inquisition|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> coupled with other migrations dating from the 1700s<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0005_0_05317.html |title=Jews migration in the 1700s|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> and during [[World War II]] <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html |title=Jews migration to the Dominican Republic to seek refuge from the Holocaust|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> contributed to Dominican ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geschichteinchronologie.ch/am-M/santo-domingo/EncJud_juden-in-Santo-Domingo-ENGL.html |title=A partial, brief summary of Jews in the Dominican Republic |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626162005/http://www.geschichteinchronologie.ch/am-M/santo-domingo/EncJud_juden-in-Santo-Domingo-ENGL.html |archive-date=2013-06-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblediscovered.com/jewish-hebrew-people-in-the-world/dominican-republic-jews-2/ |title=Dominican Republic-Jews |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001221327/https://www.biblediscovered.com/jewish-hebrew-people-in-the-world/dominican-republic-jews-2/ |archive-date=2013-10-01 }}</ref> Some of the Sephardic Jews still presently reside in [[Sos\u00faa]] while others are dispersed throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Ancestry_of_Dominican_Republic.PNG |title=Municipal Map of the Dominican Republic showing the Historical Ancestry |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819155046/http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Ancestry_of_Dominican_Republic.PNG |archive-date=2013-08-19 }}</ref> The number of known Jews (or those with genetic proof of Jewish ancestry and/or practiced Jewish customs/religion throughout generations) are close to 3,000; the exact number of Dominicans with Jewish lineages aren't known, however, because of intermarriage between the Jews and Dominicans over a period of more than five centuries.\n\n== Community ==\n\nThe current population of known Jews in the Dominican Republic is close to 3,000,<ref>[[History of the Jews in Latin America and the Caribbean#Current Jewish populations in the Americas and the Caribbean]]</ref> with the majority living in the capital, [[Santo Domingo]], and others residing in [[Sos\u00faa]]. Since Jews mixed with those already living in the Dominican Republic, the exact number of Dominicans with Jewish ancestry isn't known. In spite of the Jews intermarriage with the Dominican people already living there, some spouses have formalized their Judaism through conversions and participate in Jewish communal life while other Sephardic Jews converted to Catholicism, still maintaining their Sephardic culture. Some Dominican Jews have also made [[aliyah]] to [[Israel]]. There are three synagogues and one Sephardic Jewish Educational Center. One is the [[Centro Israelita de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana]] in Santo Domingo, another is a [[Chabad]] outreach center also in Santo Domingo, and another is in the country's first established community in Sos\u00faa.<ref>[http://www.coxwashington.com/hp/content/reporters/stories/2007/11/11/BC_CARIB_JEWS_ADV11_COX.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116113156/http://www.coxwashington.com/hp/content/reporters/stories/2007/11/11/BC_CARIB_JEWS_ADV11_COX.html |date=2008-01-16 }} COX Newspapers article on the Jewish Community of Sosua, Dominican Republic.</ref> Beth Midrash Eleazar [http://www.bmeleazar.org], the Sephardic Educational Center, caters to those Jews who are descendants of the Sephardic Jews that migrated to Hispaniola in colonial times and later. In addition, they also provide kosher meat in the Beth Yoseph style, and supervise a small-scale kosher bakery. An \"afterschool\" at the Centro Israelita is active on a weekly basis and a chapter of the International Council of Jewish Women is also active. The Chabad outreach center [http://www.chabadominican.com/] focuses on assisting the local Jewish population reconnect with their Jewish roots and (because Chabad is of the [[Chassidic]] Jewish tradition) it is a source for traditional Judaism in the Dominican Republic. In Sosua, there is a small Jewish Museum next to the synagogue. On the High Holidays, the Sosua community hires a [[Hazzan|cantor]] from abroad who comes to lead services.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Research ==\nA great deal of research on the subject of Dominican Jewry was done by Rabbi Henry Zvi Ucko<ref>[http://www.lib.unc.edu/mss/inv/u/Ucko,Henry_Zvi.html Information about the Henry Zvi Ucko papers located at The University of North Carolina]</ref> who had been a writer and teacher in [[Germany]] until political conditions and growing anti-Semitism forced him to emigrate{{when|date=November 2014}}. His travels eventually took him to the Dominican Republic, where he organized a congregation in Santo Domingo (Ciudad Trujillo) and began researching the history of Jews in the country. His research covered much of the history of the [[Sephardic Jews]] there and documented the assimilation that the population went through (and was going through) during his time. Included in his research is correspondence with Haim Horacio L\u00f3pez Penha, a Dominican Jewish writer, who encouraged Ucko to write a history of the Jews in the Dominican Republic. More recently, the publication of the book \"Once Jews\" has made easily available information on many early Jewish settlers in the Dominican Republic. Scholars such as the historian of the town of [[Ban\u00ed]], Manuel Valera, as well as Dr. Yehonatan Demota, continue the study of Dominican Sephardic and converso ancestry, and the question of the Dominican [[anusim]].\n\n== References ==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2017}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sosua-villas.com/sosua/history-of-sosua History of Sosua, Dominican Republic]\n* [http://64.177.15.143/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&products_id=683 \"Once Jews\"]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html More about the Sosua Community]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090616082321/http://www.bowdoin.edu/faculty/a/awells/tropical-zion/ Tropical Zion: General Trujillo, FDR, and the Jews of Sos\u00faa] by Allen Wells\n* [http://www.sosuamuseum.org/ Sosua Virtual Museum]\n\n{{Ancestry and ethnicity in Dominican Republic}}\n\n[[Category:History of the Dominican Republic|Jews]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in the Dominican Republic|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Rescue of Jews during the Holocaust|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Jewish history by country|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:History of the Jews in the Caribbean|History of the Jews in the Caribbean]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Centro Israelita de Republica Dominicana.JPG|thumb|right|Inside a [[Centro Israelita de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana|Santo Domingo synagogue]]]]\nThe first [[Jews]] known to have reached the island of [[Hispaniola]] were [[Spanish Jews|Spanish]].\n\nWhen the island was divided by the French and the Spanish, most Jews settled on the Spanish side which would later become the [[Dominican Republic]]. Eventually, [[Sephardim]] from other countries also arrived. In the 19th century Jews from [[Cura\u00e7ao]] settled in Hispaniola, although they did not form a strong community. Most of them hid their Jewish identities or were unaffiliated with Jewish tradition by that time. Among their descendants were Dominican President [[Francisco Henr\u00edquez y Carvajal]]<ref>[http://www.27febrero.com/biografias.htm#FRANCISCO%20HENRIQUEZ%20Y%20CARVAJAL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113182604/http://www.27febrero.com/biografias.htm#ULISES%20FRANCISCO%20ESPAILLAT |date=2008-01-13 }} Biography of Francisco Henr\u00edquez y Carvajal (in Spanish)</ref><ref name=Genealog>{{cite journal |title=Familias capitale\u00f1as: Los Henr\u00edquez |journal=C\u00e1psulas Geneal\u00f3gicas |date=23 August 2010 |issue=1/3 |url=http://hoy.com.do/capsulas-genealogicasfamilias-capitalenas-los-henriquez/ |access-date=3 February 2014 |last=Read|first=Jaime |publisher=Hoy |location=Santo Domingo |language=Spanish |quote=Este apellido se origina en la pen\u00ednsula Ib\u00e9rica, tanto en Portugal como en Espa\u00f1a, de familias jud\u00edas sefard\u00edes que marcharon posteriormente hacia el norte, llegando a Holanda, a ra\u00edz de la expulsi\u00f3n de jud\u00edos luego de la Reconquista. De all\u00ed parten hacia las colonias neerlandesas del Caribe, llegando a Curazao. En la Rep\u00fablica Dominicana, el tronco de esta familia fue Noel Henr\u00edquez Alt\u00edas (n. 25 diciembre de 1813), natural de Curazao}}</ref> and his issue [[Pedro Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]], [[Max Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]], and [[Camila Henr\u00edquez Ure\u00f1a]].\n\nThe Dominican Republic was one of the very few countries willing to accept mass Jewish immigration during [[World War II]]. At the [[\u00c9vian Conference]], it offered to accept up to 100,000 Jewish refugees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/article.php?lang=en&ModuleId=10005468|title=German Jewish Refugees, 1933\u20131939|website=www.ushmm.org|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> It is estimated that 5,000 visas were actually issued, and the vast majority of the recipients did not reach the country because of how hard it was to get out of occupied Europe.<ref name=\"bh.org.il\">{{cite web |title=The Jews of the Dominican Republic |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/dominican-republic |publisher=The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot}}</ref> The DORSA (Dominican Republic Settlement Association) was formed with the assistance of the JDC, and helped settle Jews in [[Sos\u00faa]], on the northern coast. About 700 European Jews of [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish descent reached the settlement where each family received {{Convert|33|ha}} of land, 10 cows (plus 2 additional cows per child), a mule and a horse, and a [[US$]]10,000 loan (about {{Inflation|US|10000|1941|r=-3|fmt=c}} dollars at {{currentyear}} prices) at 1% interest.<ref name=MuKienAdrianaSang>{{cite web|last=Sang|first=Mu-Kien Adriana|title=Jud\u00edos en el Caribe. La comunidad jud\u00eda en Sos\u00faa (2)|url=http://www.elcaribe.com.do/2012/11/16/judios-caribe.-comunidad-judia-sosua-2|publisher=El Caribe|access-date=29 May 2014|authorlink=Mu-Kien Adriana Sang|language=Spanish|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529071312/http://www.elcaribe.com.do/2012/11/16/judios-caribe.-comunidad-judia-sosua-2|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html|title=Dominican Republic as Haven for Jewish Refugees|website=www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Other refugees settled in the capital, Santo Domingo. In 1943 the number of known Jews in the Dominican Republic peaked at 1000. Sos\u00faa\u2019s Jewish community experienced a deep decline in the 1980s due to emigration during the touristic boom of Sos\u00faa when most Jews sold their land to developers. The oldest Jewish grave is dated to 1826.\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Sephardic Jews]] that were exiled from [[Spain]] and the Mediterranean area in 1492 and 1497,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/History/Inquisition.html |title=The Exile of the Jews due to the Spanish Inquisition|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> coupled with other migrations dating from the 1700s<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0005_0_05317.html |title=Jews migration in the 1700s|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> and during [[World War II]] <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html |title=Jews migration to the Dominican Republic to seek refuge from the Holocaust|access-date=2013-05-15}}</ref> contributed to Dominican ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geschichteinchronologie.ch/am-M/santo-domingo/EncJud_juden-in-Santo-Domingo-ENGL.html |title=A partial, brief summary of Jews in the Dominican Republic |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626162005/http://www.geschichteinchronologie.ch/am-M/santo-domingo/EncJud_juden-in-Santo-Domingo-ENGL.html |archive-date=2013-06-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblediscovered.com/jewish-hebrew-people-in-the-world/dominican-republic-jews-2/ |title=Dominican Republic-Jews |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001221327/https://www.biblediscovered.com/jewish-hebrew-people-in-the-world/dominican-republic-jews-2/ |archive-date=2013-10-01 }}</ref> Some of the Sephardic Jews still presently reside in [[Sos\u00faa]] while others are dispersed throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Ancestry_of_Dominican_Republic.PNG |title=Municipal Map of the Dominican Republic showing the Historical Ancestry |access-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819155046/http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Ancestry_of_Dominican_Republic.PNG |archive-date=2013-08-19 }}</ref> The number of known Jews (or those with genetic proof of Jewish ancestry and/or practiced Jewish customs/religion throughout generations) are close to 3,000; the exact number of Dominicans with Jewish lineages aren't known, however, because of intermarriage between the Jews and Dominicans over a period of more than five centuries.\n\n== Community ==\n\nThe current population of known Jews in the Dominican Republic is close to 3,000,<ref>[[History of the Jews in Latin America and the Caribbean#Current Jewish populations in the Americas and the Caribbean]]</ref> with the majority living in the capital, [[Santo Domingo]], and others residing in [[Sos\u00faa]]. Since Jews mixed with those already living in the Dominican Republic, the exact number of Dominicans with Jewish ancestry isn't known. In spite of the Jews intermarriage with the Dominican people already living there, some spouses have formalized their Judaism through conversions and participate in Jewish communal life while other Sephardic Jews converted to Catholicism, still maintaining their Sephardic culture. Some Dominican Jews have also made [[aliyah]] to [[Israel]]. There are three synagogues and one Sephardic Jewish Educational Center. One is the [[Centro Israelita de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana]] in Santo Domingo, another is a [[Chabad]] outreach center also in Santo Domingo, and another is in the country's first established community in Sos\u00faa.<ref>[http://www.coxwashington.com/hp/content/reporters/stories/2007/11/11/BC_CARIB_JEWS_ADV11_COX.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116113156/http://www.coxwashington.com/hp/content/reporters/stories/2007/11/11/BC_CARIB_JEWS_ADV11_COX.html |date=2008-01-16 }} COX Newspapers article on the Jewish Community of Sosua, Dominican Republic.</ref> Beth Midrash Eleazar [http://www.bmeleazar.org], the Sephardic Educational Center, caters to those Jews who are descendants of the Sephardic Jews that migrated to Hispaniola in colonial times and later. In addition, they also provide kosher meat in the Beth Yoseph style, and supervise a small-scale kosher bakery. An \"afterschool\" at the Centro Israelita is active on a weekly basis and a chapter of the International Council of Jewish Women is also active. The Chabad outreach center [http://www.chabadominican.com/] focuses on assisting the local Jewish population reconnect with their Jewish roots and (because Chabad is of the [[Chassidic]] Jewish tradition) it is a source for traditional Judaism in the Dominican Republic. In Sosua, there is a small Jewish Museum next to the synagogue. On the High Holidays, the Sosua community hires a [[Hazzan|cantor]] from abroad who comes to lead services.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Research ==\nA great deal of research on the subject of Dominican Jewry was done by Rabbi Henry Zvi Ucko<ref>[http://www.lib.unc.edu/mss/inv/u/Ucko,Henry_Zvi.html Information about the Henry Zvi Ucko papers located at The University of North Carolina]</ref> who had been a writer and teacher in [[Germany]] until political conditions and growing anti-Semitism forced him to emigrate{{when|date=November 2014}}. His travels eventually took him to the Dominican Republic, where he organized a congregation in Santo Domingo (Ciudad Trujillo) and began researching the history of Jews in the country. His research covered much of the history of the [[Sephardic Jews]] there and documented the assimilation that the population went through (and was going through) during his time. Included in his research is correspondence with Haim Horacio L\u00f3pez Penha, a Dominican Jewish writer, who encouraged Ucko to write a history of the Jews in the Dominican Republic. More recently, the publication of the book \"Once Jews\" has made easily available information on many early Jewish settlers in the Dominican Republic. Scholars such as the historian of the town of [[Ban\u00ed]], Manuel Valera, as well as Dr. Yehonatan Demota, continue the study of Dominican Sephardic and converso ancestry, and the question of the Dominican [[anusim]].\n\n== References ==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2017}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sosua-villas.com/sosua/history-of-sosua History of Sosua, Dominican Republic]\n* [http://64.177.15.143/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&products_id=683 \"Once Jews\"]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/sosua.html More about the Sosua Community]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090616082321/http://www.bowdoin.edu/faculty/a/awells/tropical-zion/ Tropical Zion: General Trujillo, FDR, and the Jews of Sos\u00faa] by Allen Wells\n* [http://www.sosuamuseum.org/ Sosua Virtual Museum]\n\n{{Ancestry and ethnicity in Dominican Republic}}\n\n[[Category:History of the Dominican Republic|Jews]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in the Dominican Republic|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Rescue of Jews during the Holocaust|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Jewish history by country|Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:History of the Jews in the Caribbean|History of the Jews in the Caribbean]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_Dominican_Republic"}
{"title_page": "Rafa Sardina", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Rafa Sardina\n| image            = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Rafael Sardina\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Bermeo]]<br />\n[[Spain]]\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = *[[Mixing engineer]]\n*[[Recording engineer]]\n*[[Record producer]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist}}\n* [[Alejandro Sanz]]\n* [[Luis Miguel]]\n* [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]]\n* [[Lady Gaga]]\n* [[Armando Manzanero]]\n* [[D'Angelo]]\n* The Clare Fischer Big Band\n}}\n'''Rafael Sardina''', known professionally as Rafa Sardina, is a [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|basque]] [[Audio engineer|recording engineer]], [[mixing engineer]] and [[record producer]] known for his work with [[Alejandro Sanz]], [[Luis Miguel]], [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]], [[D'Angelo]], [[Clare Fischer|The Clare Fischer Big Band]] and [[Lady Gaga]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rafa-sardina-mn0000385915|title=Rafa Sardina {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixonline.com/recording/producer-engineer-rafa-sardina|title=Producer/Engineer Rafa Sardina|date=2019-03-04|website=Mixonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nSardina has won 5 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/rafa-sardina|title=Rafa Sardina|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/dangelo|title=D'Angelo|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and 10 [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/nominees/search|title=20a Entrega Anual del Latin GRAMMY|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He is the current governor of the [[The Recording Academy|Recording Academy]], Los Angeles Chapter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aes.org/events/145/presenters/?ID=7496|title=AES New York 2018 \u00bb Presenters: Rafa Sardina|website=www.aes.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and has served on the Board of Trustees of the [[The Latin Recording Academy|Latin Recording Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/the-latin-recording-academy-elects-new-trustees|title=The Latin Recording Academy elects new Trustees|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/the-latin-recording-academy-elects-new-officers-to-its-board-of-trustees|title=The Latin Recording Academy\u00ae elects new officers to its Board of Trustees|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Sardina is a founding member and vice chairman of the Latin Recording Academy's CPI (''C\u00edrculo de Productores e Ingenieros''), equivalent to the Producers and Engineers Wing of the Recording Academy<ref name=\":1\" />. He was the executive producer of the 2017 and 2018 [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year]] galas honoring [[Alejandro Sanz]] and [[Man\u00e1]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/anitta-nacho-arimany-diego-el-negro-lvarez-ismael-fern-ndez-siudy-garrido-manuel-medrano-jes-s|title=Anitta, Nacho Arimany, Diego \"El Negro\" \u00c1lvarez, Ismael Fern\u00e1ndez, Siudy Garrido, Manuel Medrano, Jes\u00fas Montoya, and Jos\u00e9 Antonio Rodr\u00edguez join the 2017 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year gala honoring Alejandro Sanz|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/alejandro-sanz-named-2017-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year|title=Alejandro Sanz named 2017 Latin Recording Academy\u00ae Person of the Year|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/gala-to-honor-alejandro-sanz-with-2017-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year-distinction|title=Gala to honor Alejandro Sanz with 2017 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year\u2122 distinction will showcase performances by David Bisbal, Camila Cabello, Santiago Cruz, Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez, Luis Fonsi, Juan Luis Guerra, Jesse & Joy, Juanes...|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/man-named-2018-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year|title=Man\u00e1 named 2018 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year\u2122|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSardina was born in [[Bermeo]], a fishing port in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]] located in northern [[Spain]]. Sardina's interest in music started at a young age. At the age of 6, he secretly played his younger sister's guitar and later told his mother he wanted to become a professional musician.\n\nHis parents moved to [[San Diego|San Diego, California]] when he was 15. After a couple of months, Sardina returned to Spain, finished school and started playing in bands. His first experience in a recording studio was at age 16, when he attended a recording session of his cousin's band in [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]].\n\nSardina joined medical school at age 16. During his second year of school, he started working as [[Live sound mixing|front of house]] and [[Live sound mixing|monitor engineer]] for local acts. During his fourth year of school and right before taking the final exam, Sardina decided to drop out. He saved up for a three-week recording certification program at [[Recording Workshop|The Recording Workshop]] school in [[Chillicothe, Ohio]]. Sardina then went back to Spain and continued saving until he enrolled in a program at [[Full Sail University]] in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n\nIn 1993, four weeks before graduating with a Valedictorian Award,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fullsail.edu/about/full-sail-stories/alumni-credited-on-latin-grammy-nominated-projects|title=Seventeen Alumni Credited on Latin GRAMMY Nominated Projects|website=www.fullsail.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imsta.org/panelists/rafa_sardina.php|title=Panelist Biography|website=www.imsta.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Sardina organized a 24-hour trip to [[Los Angeles]]. He did interviews at [[Record Plant]], [[Westlake Recording Studios]] and [[Ocean Way Recording]], where he later started working and became assistant engineer. During his time at Ocean Way, Sardina recorded artists including [[Celine Dion]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Dr. Dre]] and [[David Foster]].\n\nIn 2001, after working for 5 years at Ocean Way, Sardina founded Fishbone Productions and started working as an independent engineer, recording at his studio \"AfterHours\". Sardina became better known for his work on [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] and [[Latin music|Latin]] records, although he also works on a variety of genres including [[Jazz]], [[Orchestra|Orchestral]], [[Gospel music|Gospel]], [[World music|World]] and [[Soundtrack|Film/TV soundtracks]]. He continued working with artists including [[Alejandro Sanz]], [[Luis Miguel]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Lady Gaga]] and [[D'Angelo]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSardina engineered the album \"Symphonic Soweto: A Tribute To Nelson Mandela\", which won the South African Music Award for Best Contemporary Album in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aes.org/events/145/presenters/?ID=7496|title=AES New York 2018 \u00bb Presenters: Rafa Sardina|website=www.aes.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/lifestyle/samas2018-all-the-winners-at-this-years-awards/|title=#SAMAs 2018: Full list of the winners from this year's awards|date=2018-06-03|work=The South African|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== AfterHours Studios ==\nSardina founded AfterHours Studios to record his projects. AfterHours was first located at his previous house. Sardina describes it as being ''\"just a tiny room, tracking little things like drums in the hallway\"''.\n\nThe studio is now located in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]], where he remodeled a two story three-car garage and an adjacent room. The live room, control room and isolation booth are on the first floor, while an office and a lounge are located on the second floor. The studio operates around a [[Solid State Logic]] Duality console and incorporates multiple [[Effects unit|outboard processors]] into a [[Digital audio workstation|digital recording system]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prosoundnetwork.com/recording/its-always-after-hours-for-rafa-sardina|title=It\u2019s Always After Hours for Rafa Sardina|date=2016-12-15|website=ProSoundNetwork.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The studio was featured on [[Mix (magazine)|Mix Magazine's]] Class of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixonline.com/recording/class-2017-429899|title=Class Of 2017|date=2017-06-14|website=Mixonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n=== [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artist\n!Category\n!Role\n!Result\n|-\n|[[46th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n|[[No Es lo Mismo|No Es Lo Mismo]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[48th Annual Grammy Awards|2006]]\n|[[M\u00e9xico en la Piel (album)|M\u00e9xico En La Piel]]\n|[[Luis Miguel]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[50th Annual Grammy Awards|2008]]\n|[[El Tren de los Momentos]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[58th Annual Grammy Awards|2016]]\n|[[Really Love]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[D'Angelo|D'Angelo & The Vanguard]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Black Messiah (album)|Black Messiah]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album|Best R&B Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[59th Annual Grammy Awards|2017]]\n|[[Buena Vida (album)|Buena Vida]]\n|[[Diego Torres (singer)|Diego Torres]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|L.H.O.N.\n|[[Illya Kuryaki and the Valderramas|Illya Kuryaki & The Valderramas]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album|Best Latin, Rock, Urban or Alternative Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n|[[El Disco|#Eldisco]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Indestructible\n|Flor de Toloache\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album|Best Latin, Rock, Urban or Alternative Album]]\n|Engineer|Producer, Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|}\n<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/diego-torres|title=Diego Torres|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/illya-kuryaki-valderramas|title=Illya Kuryaki & The Valderramas|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/62nd-annual-grammy-awards-2019|title=62nd Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}<