 Vocal Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[15th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2014]]\n|[[Multi Viral|MultiViral]]\n|[[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[16th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2015]]\n|[[Sirope]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |[[17th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2016]]\n| -\n| -\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year|Producer of the Year]]\n|Producer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Iguales\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Diego Torres (singer)|Diego Torres]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Buena Vida (album)|Buena Vida]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album|Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|L.H.O.N.\n|[[Illya Kuryaki and the Valderramas|Illya Kuryaki & The Valderramas]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[18th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2017]]\n|Quiero Que Vuelvas\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Rompiendo Fronteras]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album|Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[19th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2018]]\n|50 A\u00f1os Tocando Para Ti\n|Orquesta Filarm\u00f3nica de Bogot\u00e1\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album|Best Engineered Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[20th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2019]]\n| -\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Producer of the Year|Producer of the Year]]\n|Producer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Indestructible\n|Flor de Toloache\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Ranchero/Mariachi Album|Best Ranchero/Mariachi Album]]\n|Producer, Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[El Disco|#Eldisco]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|Engineer|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|No Tengo Nada\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|Engineer|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[El Disco|#Eldisco]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album|Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album]]\n|Engineer|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Amor Presente\n|Leonel Garc\u00eda\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Singer-Songwriter Album|Best Singer-Songwriter Album]]\n|Engineer|Engineer\n|{{Nom}}\n|}\n<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resolutionmag.com/news/latin-grammys-rafa-sardina-wins-best-engineered-album/|title=Resolution Magazine|website=Resolution Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alborde.com/musica-section/2014-latin-grammy-nominations/|title=2014 Latin Grammy Nominations|last=Aguilar|first=Angel|date=2014-09-24|website=Al Borde|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.prosoundnetwork.com/recording/its-always-after-hours-for-rafa-sardina Interview with Rafa Sardina | Latin Recording Academy]\n* [https://www.pensadosplace.tv/engineerproducermixer-rafa-sardina/ Pensado's Place #279 | Engineer/Producer/Mixer Rafa Sardina]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sardina, Rafa}}\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Full Sail University alumni]]\n[[Category:Latin music record producers]]\n[[Category:People from Bermeo]]\n[[Category:Spanish record producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Rafa Sardina\n| image            = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Rafael Sardina\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Bermeo]]<br />\n[[Spain]]\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = *[[Mixing engineer]]\n*[[Recording engineer]]\n*[[Record producer]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist}}\n* [[Alejandro Sanz]]\n* [[Luis Miguel]]\n* [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]]\n* [[Lady Gaga]]\n* [[Armando Manzanero]]\n* [[D'Angelo]]\n* The Clare Fischer Big Band\n}}\n'''Rafael Sardina''', known professionally as Rafa Sardina, is a [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|basque]] [[Audio engineer|recording engineer]], [[mixing engineer]] and [[record producer]] known for his work with [[Alejandro Sanz]], [[Luis Miguel]], [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]], [[D'Angelo]], [[Clare Fischer|The Clare Fischer Big Band]] and [[Lady Gaga]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rafa-sardina-mn0000385915|title=Rafa Sardina {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixonline.com/recording/producer-engineer-rafa-sardina|title=Producer/Engineer Rafa Sardina|date=2019-03-04|website=Mixonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nSardina has won 5 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/rafa-sardina|title=Rafa Sardina|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/dangelo|title=D'Angelo|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and 10 [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/nominees/search|title=20a Entrega Anual del Latin GRAMMY|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He is the current governor of the [[The Recording Academy|Recording Academy]] Los Angeles Chapter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aes.org/events/145/presenters/?ID=7496|title=AES New York 2018 \u00bb Presenters: Rafa Sardina|website=www.aes.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and has served on the Board of Trustees of the [[The Latin Recording Academy|Latin Recording Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/the-latin-recording-academy-elects-new-trustees|title=The Latin Recording Academy elects new Trustees|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/the-latin-recording-academy-elects-new-officers-to-its-board-of-trustees|title=The Latin Recording Academy\u00ae elects new officers to its Board of Trustees|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Sardina is a founding member and vice chairman of the Latin Recording Academy's CPI (''C\u00edrculo de Productores e Ingenieros''), equivalent to the Producers and Engineers Wing of the Recording Academy<ref name=\":1\" />. He was the executive producer of the 2017 and 2018 [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year]] galas honoring [[Alejandro Sanz]] and [[Man\u00e1]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/anitta-nacho-arimany-diego-el-negro-lvarez-ismael-fern-ndez-siudy-garrido-manuel-medrano-jes-s|title=Anitta, Nacho Arimany, Diego \"El Negro\" \u00c1lvarez, Ismael Fern\u00e1ndez, Siudy Garrido, Manuel Medrano, Jes\u00fas Montoya, and Jos\u00e9 Antonio Rodr\u00edguez join the 2017 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year gala honoring Alejandro Sanz|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/alejandro-sanz-named-2017-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year|title=Alejandro Sanz named 2017 Latin Recording Academy\u00ae Person of the Year|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/gala-to-honor-alejandro-sanz-with-2017-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year-distinction|title=Gala to honor Alejandro Sanz with 2017 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year\u2122 distinction will showcase performances by David Bisbal, Camila Cabello, Santiago Cruz, Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez, Luis Fonsi, Juan Luis Guerra, Jesse & Joy, Juanes...|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latingrammy.com/en/news/man-named-2018-latin-recording-academy-person-of-the-year|title=Man\u00e1 named 2018 Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year\u2122|website=Latin GRAMMYs|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSardina was born in [[Bermeo]], a fishing port in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]] located in northern [[Spain]]. Sardina's interest in music started at a young age. At the age of 6, he secretly played his younger sister's guitar and later told his mother he wanted to become a professional musician.\n\nHis parents moved to [[San Diego|San Diego, California]] when he was 15. After a couple of months, Sardina returned to Spain, finished school and started playing in bands. His first experience in a recording studio was at age 16, when he attended a recording session of his cousin's band in [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]].\n\nSardina joined medical school at age 16. During his second year of school, he started working as [[Live sound mixing|front of house]] and [[Live sound mixing|monitor engineer]] for local acts. During his fourth year of school and right before taking the final exam, Sardina decided to drop out. He saved up for a three-week recording certification program at [[Recording Workshop|The Recording Workshop]] school in [[Chillicothe, Ohio]]. Sardina then went back to Spain and continued saving until he enrolled in a program at [[Full Sail University]] in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n\nIn 1993, four weeks before graduating with a Valedictorian Award,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fullsail.edu/about/full-sail-stories/alumni-credited-on-latin-grammy-nominated-projects|title=Seventeen Alumni Credited on Latin GRAMMY Nominated Projects|website=www.fullsail.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imsta.org/panelists/rafa_sardina.php|title=Panelist Biography|website=www.imsta.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Sardina organized a 24-hour trip to [[Los Angeles]]. He did interviews at [[Record Plant]], [[Westlake Recording Studios]] and [[Ocean Way Recording]], where he later started working and became assistant engineer. During his time at Ocean Way, Sardina recorded artists including [[Celine Dion]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Dr. Dre]] and [[David Foster]].\n\nIn 2001, after working for 5 years at Ocean Way, Sardina founded Fishbone Productions and started working as an independent engineer, recording at his studio \"AfterHours\". Sardina became better known for his work on [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] and [[Latin music|Latin]] records, although he also works on a variety of genres including [[Jazz]], [[Orchestra|Orchestral]], [[Gospel music|Gospel]], [[World music|World]] and [[Soundtrack|Film/TV soundtracks]]. He continued working with artists including [[Alejandro Sanz]], [[Luis Miguel]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Lady Gaga]] and [[D'Angelo]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSardina engineered the album \"Symphonic Soweto: A Tribute To Nelson Mandela\", which won the South African Music Award for Best Contemporary Album in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aes.org/events/145/presenters/?ID=7496|title=AES New York 2018 \u00bb Presenters: Rafa Sardina|website=www.aes.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/lifestyle/samas2018-all-the-winners-at-this-years-awards/|title=#SAMAs 2018: Full list of the winners from this year's awards|date=2018-06-03|work=The South African|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== AfterHours Studios ==\nSardina founded AfterHours Studios to record his projects. AfterHours was first located at his previous house. Sardina describes it as being ''\"just a tiny room, tracking little things like drums in the hallway\"''.\n\nThe studio is now located in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]], where he remodeled a two story three-car garage and an adjacent room. The live room, control room and isolation booth are on the first floor, while an office and a lounge are located on the second floor. The studio operates around a [[Solid State Logic]] Duality console and incorporates multiple [[Effects unit|outboard processors]] into a [[Digital audio workstation|digital recording system]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prosoundnetwork.com/recording/its-always-after-hours-for-rafa-sardina|title=It\u2019s Always After Hours for Rafa Sardina|date=2016-12-15|website=ProSoundNetwork.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The studio was featured on [[Mix (magazine)|Mix Magazine's]] Class of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixonline.com/recording/class-2017-429899|title=Class Of 2017|date=2017-06-14|website=Mixonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n=== [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artist\n!Category\n!Role\n!Result\n|-\n|[[46th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n|[[No Es lo Mismo|No Es Lo Mismo]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[48th Annual Grammy Awards|2006]]\n|[[M\u00e9xico en la Piel (album)|M\u00e9xico En La Piel]]\n|[[Luis Miguel]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[50th Annual Grammy Awards|2008]]\n|[[El Tren de los Momentos]]\n|[[Alejandro Sanz]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|Engineer\n|{{Won}}\n|